---
title: Split Panel
description: "Two side-by-side panels where the left panel can be drag-resized using CSS `resize: horizontal` — no JavaScript."
slug: split-panel
cssFile: split-panel.css
explanation: "`resize: horizontal` tells the browser to render a native drag handle on the element. It requires `overflow` to be set to anything other than `visible` — here `overflow: auto` handles scrolling if content overflows while also enabling the resize. `min-width` and `max-width` prevent the panel from collapsing entirely or consuming the full container. The right panel uses `flex: 1` to fill the remaining space automatically."
---
{% extends "example.njk" %}
{% block demo %}
<div class="demo-split-panel">
	<div class="split-left">
		<span class="split-label">// Files</span>
		<div class="split-item">index.njk</div>
		<div class="split-item">global.css</div>
		<div class="split-item">eleventy.config.js</div>
		<div class="split-item">allExamples.js</div>
		<div class="split-item">base.njk</div>
		<span class="split-hint">drag corner ↘ to resize</span>
	</div>
	<div class="split-right">
		<span class="split-label">// Preview</span>
		<div class="split-item">← select a file to preview</div>
	</div>
</div>
{% endblock %}

{% block html_code %}
{%- highlight "html" %}
<div class="split-container">
  <div class="split-left">
    <!-- resizable panel -->
  </div>
  <div class="split-right">
    <!-- fills remaining space -->
  </div>
</div>
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}

{% block css_code %}
{%- highlight "css" %}
.split-container {
  display: flex;
}

.split-left {
  resize: horizontal;
  overflow: auto;   /* required for resize to work */
  min-width: 80px;
  max-width: 70%;
  width: 45%;
}

.split-right {
  flex: 1; /* fill the rest */
}
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}
